# Git Flow Guide

This guide explains how to use Git for day-to-day collaboration on the **Barista Coffee Membership** project.  
For: BA, Developer, Tester joining the project.

---

## What is Git?

Git is a system that tracks every change made to the project over time. Think of it like a detailed version history for the entire project — not just one file, but everything.

Every saved checkpoint is called a **commit**. Each commit has:
- A message describing what changed
- A timestamp
- The name of who made the change

This means the team can always see what was done, when, and by whom — and roll back if something goes wrong.

---

## Core Concepts

| Term | Simple Meaning |
|---|---|
| **Repository (repo)** | The project folder, tracked by Git |
| **Branch** | An independent copy of the project to work on safely |
| **main** | The main branch — the official, stable version |
| **Stage** | Selecting which changes you want to include in the next commit |
| **Commit** | Saving a checkpoint with a message |
| **Push** | Uploading your commits to GitHub so others can see them |
| **Pull** | Downloading the latest changes from GitHub to your machine |
| **Conflict** | Two people edited the same part of the same file — Git needs help deciding which version to keep |

---

## Daily Workflow

### The Golden Rule
> **Always Pull before you start working.** This ensures you have the latest version before making any changes.

---

### Step-by-step: A typical working session

```
1. Pull latest changes from GitHub
2. Make your changes (edit files, add documents, etc.)
3. Stage the files you changed
4. Commit with a clear message
5. Push to GitHub
```

---

## How to Do It in Kiro (for BA)

### Pull — get latest changes before starting

1. Open the **Source Control** tab (left sidebar, branch icon)
2. Click the **⋯** menu at the top of the panel
3. Select **Pull**

> Always do this at the start of every working session.

---

### Stage — select what to save

1. In **Source Control**, you will see your changed files listed under **Changes**
2. Click the **+** icon next to **Changes** to stage all files
3. Or click **+** next to individual files to stage only specific ones

---

### Commit — save a checkpoint

1. Type a short message in the **Message** box at the top
2. Press **Commit**

**Commit message examples:**
- `Add PRD document`
- `Update user stories epic 1`
- `Fix typo in requirements`

Keep messages short and descriptive — your teammates will read them.

---

### Push — upload to GitHub

1. After committing, the button changes to **Sync Changes ↑**
2. Click it to push your commits to GitHub

---

## How to Do It in Terminal (for Developer)

### Pull
```bash
git pull
```

### Stage all changes
```bash
git add .
```

### Stage specific files only
```bash
git add docs/SETUP.md
```

### Commit
```bash
git commit -m "Add PRD document"
```

### Push
```bash
git push
```

