## Working as a Team — Important Rules

### 1. Always Pull first
Before you start any work, pull the latest version. This prevents most conflicts.

### 2. Communicate before editing the same file
If two people edit the same file at the same time, a conflict may occur. A quick message on Slack like *"I'm updating the PRD now"* saves a lot of trouble.

### 3. Commit often, in small chunks
Don't wait until you've changed 20 files to commit. Commit each logical unit of work separately. It's easier to review and easier to undo if needed.

### 4. Never push directly to main (for developers)
Developers should work on a separate branch and open a Pull Request to merge into `main`. BAs working on documents can commit directly to `main` for simplicity.

---

## What is a Conflict?

A conflict happens when two people edit the **same lines** in the **same file** and both push their changes. Git cannot automatically decide which version to keep, so it asks you.

**How to avoid it:**
- Pull before starting work
- Communicate with teammates when editing shared documents

**How to resolve it in Kiro:**
1. Kiro will highlight the conflicting file in red in Source Control
2. Open the file — you will see both versions marked clearly
3. Choose which version to keep (or combine them)
4. Stage and commit the resolved file

